WEBVTT

00:00:00.190 --> 00:00:04.650
PyAnalySeries provides several methods to estimate the power spectral density

00:00:04.650 --> 00:00:05.360
of a signal.

00:00:06.700 --> 00:00:10.410
These methods rely on the Pyleoclim module, which itself builds

00:00:10.410 --> 00:00:12.950
on spectral analysis methods available in SciPy.

00:00:13.050 --> 00:00:17.420
The goal here is to make these methods easily accessible

00:00:17.620 --> 00:00:20.720
within the application, so they can be tested and compared

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:21.640
interactively.

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:26.060
For each method, the most essential parameters have been exposed

00:00:26.060 --> 00:00:29.610
in the interface, allowing quick exploration of the different spectral

00:00:29.610 --> 00:00:30.460
estimators.

00:00:31.710 --> 00:00:33.330
Let’s return to our example.

00:00:34.470 --> 00:00:37.100
We use the “ PercAndes ” series to investigate its

00:00:37.100 --> 00:00:41.900
significant periodicities, using the different methods on the original, resampled

00:00:41.930 --> 00:00:43.290
or smoothed series.

00:00:44.430 --> 00:00:47.850
Select a series, then go to Process and choose “

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:52.670
Spectral Estimation ”, with PSD standing for Power Spectral Density

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:56.920
The Periodogram is the most direct estimator of the power

00:00:56.920 --> 00:00:58.570
spectral density.

00:00:58.570 --> 00:01:01.300
It is simple and easy to interpret, but it can

00:01:01.300 --> 00:01:02.260
be noisy.

00:01:04.380 --> 00:01:07.070
The idea is to quickly explore the impact of different

00:01:07.070 --> 00:01:07.930
parameters.

00:01:09.130 --> 00:01:12.900
Press Compute, or simply modify a parameter, and the plot

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:14.380
updates automatically.

00:01:15.530 --> 00:01:17.870
You can clean up your tests by removing the last

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:20.570
spectrum from the stack using the “ Remove last ”

00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:21.130
option.

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:25.830
Welch’s method improves the estimate by splitting the signal into

00:01:25.870 --> 00:01:28.860
overlapping segments and averaging their spectra.

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:35.090
MTM, for Multi-Taper Method, uses several tapers to obtain a

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:36.900
more stable spectral estimate.

00:01:39.060 --> 00:01:43.560
Lomb–Scargle is especially useful for unevenly spaced time series.

00:01:45.690 --> 00:01:51.880
Wavelet analysis, using WWZ, explores how periodicities evolve through time

00:01:53.070 --> 00:01:56.850
For each method, you can access the corresponding documentation through

00:01:56.850 --> 00:01:58.020
a dedicated link.

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:02.330
Each method also has its own prerequisites, such as standardization

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:03.880
or interpolation.

00:02:07.100 --> 00:02:10.170
These steps are handled automatically by the interface, so there

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:12.170
is no need to perform them beforehand.

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:16.730
The spectrum is displayed on a logarithmic scale and fully

00:02:16.730 --> 00:02:17.760
supports zooming.

00:02:18.850 --> 00:02:22.730
Once saved, each computed spectrum appears in the main window

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:24.880
with its dedicated icon.

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:34.450
Using “ Display Together ” allows you to visualize them

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:36.100
simultaneously.

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:46.170
In practice, we compute and save the MTM and wavelet

00:02:46.170 --> 00:02:48.330
spectra on the resampled record.

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:54.750
For advanced spectral analysis, it is recommended to explore Pyleoclim

00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:59.230
in a Python or notebook environment, to fine-tune method-specific parameters

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:02.520
and ensure full reproducibility of the results.
